To follow the Greek practice closely would bring the metrical ictus into constant clash with the natural accent, a thing alien to the spirit of Latin verse (see Appendix), so that Latin Anapaests should be constructed on different principles. From a sentence of Marius Victorinus (iii. p. 77 Κ.) it appears that Pacuvius was the poet whose name was associated With a reformed type of Anapaests which better suited the genius of the Latin language.
